They're good questions because they go past the two simplest query types:<p><pre><code>    select from ... where ...;
</code></pre>
and<p><pre><code>    select from ... join ... where;
</code></pre>
Those are the types 99% of programmers who use SQL for simple CRUD apps know. But they come up short for asking more useful business questions.<p>Eyeballing the list, it tests subqueries, GROUP BY, HAVING, OUTER JOIN, IN/NOT IN and SUM. Fairly useful primitives for general query writing.<p>I'd try to add a question that relies on UNION, INTERSECT or EXCEPT.
